<TEXT>
 A 22-year-old man who faced execution by lethal injection Friday for murdering a <LOCATION> Las </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Vegas </LOCATION> store clerk during a 1986 robbery won a stay Tuesday from a federal judge. <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Pellegrini </PERSON> had initially not wanted a stay but changed his mind Monday. Assistant Federal Public Defender <PERSON> Pat </PERSON> <PERSON> Flanagan </PERSON> immediately obtained the stay from <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Phil </PERSON> <PERSON> Pro </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Las </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Vegas </LOCATION>. Pro told <PERSON> Pellegrini </PERSON> he should return to the state courts and file any post-conviction appeals possible at that level before filing any more federal court petitions. <PERSON> Pellegrini </PERSON> was sentenced to die for the slaying of <PERSON> Barry </PERSON> <PERSON> Hancock </PERSON>, 27, who was handcuffed and shot in the head. <PERSON> Flanagan </PERSON> sought a stay on grounds a prosecutor improperly suggested during a penalty hearing that there could be more victims if <PERSON> Pellegrini </PERSON> ever got out of prison. The defender also claimed authorities conducted an illegal search of <PERSON> Pellegrini </PERSON>'s apartment, where the murder weapon, bullets and blood-spattered clothes were found. The same issues were raised in a state <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> appeal, which was rejected last November when the high court held that the record provided substantial support for the verdict and the penalty.
