TION> Budget </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION>, using the administration's own economic assumptions, forecasts a $ 205 billion figure. Without coming up with its own price tag, <ORGANIZATION> GAO </ORGANIZATION> said it questioned assumptions in the rescue plan that interest rates will fall sharply from levels at the end of 1988. Higher-than-expected rates could increase financing costs and hurt shaky institutions. The <ORGANIZATION> GAO </ORGANIZATION> also said a recession, which some economists believe is likely in the next several years, could increase the number of failing thrifts. And it said deposits may grow more slowly than the plan assumes, cutting premium income. The plan could cost an extra $ 7 billion over 10 years if deposits grow at only 3 percent a year instead of the assumed 7 percent, according to Rep. Rep. <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Kanjorski </PERSON>, D-Pa., who requested the <ORGANIZATION> GAO </ORGANIZATION> study
